observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant and the OIC – GSO to evaluate the causes of the material discrepancy of ₱1,579,146,695.66 to ascertain the fairness and reliability of PPE balances in the financial statements;


Instruct the OIC – GSO to prepare and maintain complete property cards;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Make detailed evaluation and tracing of the noted unreconciled beginning balances totaling ₱154,546,441.36 to reflect the correct balances of these accounts in the financial statements;

Prepare and maintain complete PPE ledger cards for each group of PPE;



Locate records for the data needed in order to provide appropriate depreciation costs of PPE and ensure that every PPE recorded in the books is provided with depreciation cost, except Land account; and

Make the necessary adjustments in the books to derecognize properties already disposed to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts in the financial statements;

Require the Municipal Accountant and OIC – GSO as well as other concerned officials to review the guidelines and procedures of and initiate compliance to the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability; and



Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct complete physical count of all the assets and properties of the Municipality and submit the RPCPPE within the reglementary period.

We recommended that Management:

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to:

Strictly enforce the relevant provisions of the Municipal Revenue Code to ensure the proper assessment and collection of business taxes, thereby optimizing revenue for the Municipality;


Require all business establishments to submit a copy of their ITR and enforce the collection of any deficiencies in business tax based on discrepancies between declared and reported gross receipts;


Conduct regular inspections and verifications of the financial records of business establishments to ensure that the gross receipts declared are accurate and consistent with their actual operations; and

b. 	Require the Sangguniang Bayan to expedite the review and enactment of the revised Municipal Revenue Code to enhance its revenue-generating capacity and to better support programs, projects and services beneficial to the constituents.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Ensure strict adherence with the BIR, GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth regulations in the withholding of statutory deductions such as having the responsible employees undergo capacity-building activities and training sessions relevant to the subject matter;

Ensure accurate and timely recording of all amounts withheld, remitted and adjusted, if any;



Consider the preparation of separate subsidiary ledger or schedules for each account component to facilitate more efficient and transparent account reconciliation;

Regularly and accurately reconcile the balances of the Due to BIR, Due to GSIS, Due to Pag-IBIG and Due to PhilHealth accounts, and promptly effect necessary adjustments, duly supported by complete and appropriate documentation; and

Consider initiating coordination with the concerned government regulatory agencies to facilitate the reconciliation of accounts, particularly those involving prior years’ discrepancies.

We recommended that Management:

a.	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Observe proper accounting of semi-expendable properties using the prescribed new accounts; and








Record the necessary retrospective adjustments for the reclassification of items recorded under the PPE account that fall below the ₱50,000.00 threshold; 

b. 	Require the Supply Officer to:

Issue ICS for the issuance of semi-expendable properties totaling ₱1,713,126.50 and furnish copies thereof to the Audit Team;




Provide the useful life of semi-expendable properties issued in the ICS; and



Prepare and maintain the required forms, registries and reports for semi-expendable properties and assign separate ICS control numbers for low-valued items and high-valued items to strengthen the controls and safeguards over the semi-expendable properties; 

c. 	Direct the Municipal Accountant and Supply Officer to:

Maintain complete Semi-Expendable Property Ledger Card and Semi-Expendable Property Card, respectively, for each item of semi-expendable properties; and



Formulate a policy/memorandum determining the estimated useful life of semi-expendable properties, and provide a copy thereof to the Audit Team;

d. 	Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical count of semi-expendable properties still in the custody of the Supply Officer and prepare the RPCSP to verify their existence and condition.

