We recommended that Management:
Require the OIC-GSO to strictly comply with the required complete physical count of all properties at least once a year using the proper format and to submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain complete PPELC;
Require the OIC-GSO to maintain complete Property Cards;
Instruct the OIC-GSO to review all the PARs of all properties of the LGU and cause the renewal thereof when necessary especially those that were issued three years ago; and
Instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to prepare report on the differences/variances between the accounting records and the Report on the Physical Count of PPE.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the OIC-Municipal Accountant and OIC-GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, taking into account the allocation of the cost incurred for consolidated road projects to each road network based on the Program of Works;
Require the OIC-GSO to prepare the Road Map and instruct the OIC-GSO, Municipal Engineer and OIC-Municipal Accountant to reconcile the inventory of local roads with the recorded road networks in the books of accounts;
Require the OIC-GSO to prepare a Report of Local Road Network at the end of each accounting period;
Create an inventory committee or group that will primarily handle the inventory of local road network system;
Instruct the Head of the Inventory Committee to conduct annual inventory of road networks using the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network System; and
Upon reconciliation of records, require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to adjust the balance of road networks in the books of accounts and maintain subsidiary ledger for roads and road components for every road network.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Acting Municipal Treasurer, to determine and identify the specific nature of the unaccounted or undocumented reconciling items in the Bank Reconciliation Statements of the affected bank accounts;
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant together with her staff to exert extra effort in tracing/retrieving the misplaced/missing/unrecorded disbursement vouchers and other pertinent documents to effect the necessary adjustments;
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to make representation with the bank officials to obtain copies of the bank’s debit and credit memos to support the adjustments; and
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Acting Municipal Treasurer, to review and analyze as well as to locate documents of the unrecorded reconciling item  to be able to determine where the balance of the Trust Fund was deposited amounting to Ᵽ208,585.99.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to continue sending Demand Letters to accountable officers with unliquidated cash advances;
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to cause the withholding of salaries of the accountable officers concerned until they have fully settled their unliquidated cash advances;
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to issue Certification for new request of cash advances to avoid granting of additional cash advance to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given to him is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made;
Direct the Municipal Legal Officer to impose administrative sanctions against Accountable Officers (AOs) for any unjustifiable reasons on the failure to liquidate cash advances within the prescribed period, in accordance with Section 89 of PD 1445 and CSC Resolution No. 0676 dated June 17, 2004; and
Instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to request for write-off of the unliquidated cash advances of the deceased accountable officers in accordance with the procedures stated in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We reiterated the previous year’s audit recommendation that Management:
Require the PESO Officer to locate the former personnel in-charge with UNAKA loans and demand from her the records pertaining to UNAKA loans;
Instruct the PESO Officer, in coordination with the OIC-Municipal Accountant, to reconcile the records relative to OCW loan profiles/reports;
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to maintain complete and updated individual subsidiary ledgers of all beneficiaries/recipients of UNAKA and OCW loans for immediate reconciliation to determine the details of discrepancies and effect adjustments in the books; and
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to continue sending collection notices and adopt efficient and aggressive collection strategies to enforce collection to recipients/creditors concerned to generate funds for other constituents who wish to avail of the livelihood program.  If all means failed, resort to legal action in the collection of overdue receivables to avoid possible loss of government funds.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the OIC-GSO to secure the RIS or any equivalent proof that the items comprising the balance of inventory were already issued or consumed, and submit the same to the OIC-Municipal Accountant for proper adjustment in the books;
Provide a stockroom or space for the use of OIC-GSO to keep the supplies and materials to be purchased including equipment which are to be issued to the requisitioning head of department needing the same;
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to maintain Supplies Ledger Card for each specific type of Inventory;
Require the OIC-GSO to record purchases and issuances of supplies through the use of the prescribed Stock Card for each type of inventory;
Instruct the OIC-GSO to consolidate weekly the RIS using the RSMI and submit the original copies thereof to the OIC-Municipal Accountant;
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to record the inventories using the perpetual inventory system and weighted average cost method, and ensure that the relative expense will be recognized only upon the receipt of RSMI from the Supply Officer;
Instruct the OIC-GSO to issue Inventory Custodian Slip for issuance of small tangible items to end-users; and
Instruct the OIC-GSO to conduct a periodic physical count of its inventories and report the same in the prescribed RPCI and cause its submission to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year.

We recommended that Management require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:
Determine the nature of the payables and to establish the existence of valid obligations;
Verify the balances with their counterpart NGAs the amount appearing in each ledger balances through confirmation letters to reconcile the dormant accounts and make adjustments as necessary;
Determine the nature of other payables and reclassify the same to the appropriate accounts to correct the balances of the affected accounts and attach the relevant documents and analysis of the accounts to the JEV/s for any adjustment/s made;
Analyze and verify all the funds recorded under the Due to NGAs account and if the same were found to be utilized, prepare liquidation reports and other supporting documents to support the journal entries in the books of accounts for the liquidation of the fund transfer; and
Verify and summarize the cause of the negative balances and make the proper adjustment to correct the amount presented in the financial statements.

We recommended that Management require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:
Ensure that all claims for honoraria are supported with the required documentary requirements including certified true copies of the contracts to prove completed procurement projects, and the validity  and propriety of the payments of honoraria;
Submit to the Audit Team all lacking documents relative to the payments of BAC honoraria to establish the validity of claims;
Prepare journal entry to revert to the General Fund any balance of the proceeds from the sale of bid documents pursuant to DBM BC No. 2004-5A; and
Record in the books of accounts the proceeds from sale of bid documents and all other collections treated as trust receipts under “Trust Liabilities” account and maintain the corresponding subsidiary ledger.

We recommended that Management:
Refrain from charging non-priority expenses to SEF and accommodating regular expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has direct mandate to implement;
Strictly adhere with the regulations in the prioritization and utilization of the SEF as required in RA No. 7160 and DepED-DBM-DILG Joint Circular;
Review the annual budget of the LSB for CY 2021 and make the necessary realignment through supplemental budget for those appropriations which were allocated for unrelated expenditure items to SEF; and
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to strictly monitor the receipts of RPT share through check payment and release/transfer the one percent (1%) tax on real property accruing to the SEF once the checks are cleared in the bank and credited in the account of the LGU.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of allowing her personnel other than the appointed/designated Disbursing Officer to handle payroll fund account;
Instruct the Disbursing Officer/Payroll Master to lock her vault whenever she is on leave and ensure that no personnel to have access on her vault and documents;
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to ensure that all subsequent payments for unclaimed salaries/wages and othe emoluments of LGU personnel shall be made through separate DVs and are paid through checks; and
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to submit immediately all paid payrolls to the OIC-Municipal Accountant to avoid delays in the preparation of entries in the Disbursement Journal and in the submission of accounts to the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:
Require the drivers to sign and properly accomplish the trip tickets indicating all the necessary information for the control and monitoring of fuel consumption, and instruct them to ensure that passengers will sign thereon;
Instruct the gasoline station through the OIC-GSO to indicate in the individual invoices, the plate number of the vehicle requesting fuel;
Instruct the OIC-GSO to prepare Daily Gas Issue Record, Summary of Requisition and Issue Voucher, Monthly Report of Official Travels and Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption;
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to submit to the Audit Team all lacking documents pertaining to the payment of gasoline expenses charged to SEF; and
For vehicles and heavy equipment with defective fuel gauge, require the  OIC-GSO to undertake immediately the repair thereof, and shall henceforth, ensure to hold the drivers responsible for not reporting defective fuel gauge.

We recommended that Management:
Require the OIC-MENRO through the OIC-GSO to make a follow-up request for the provision of drainage system and treatment facility for the unwanted waste;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to inspect the Biodegradable Composting System and MRF to address the problems raised by the OIC-MENRO;
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide power supply system needed to run the Biodegradable Composting System;
Require the OIC-GSO to demand and secure from the supplier procedure manual for the operations of the biodegradable composting system; and
Require the OIC-GSO to conduct inspection and prepare a report on the corrosions/rust appearing on the equipment and take immediate action as necessary to treat the same to avoid deterioration of the equipment.

We recommended that Management:
Ensure the implementation of the program  for the production of IDs of residents of the Municipality and provide the Audit Team with a list or names of residents of the Municipality that already received their IDs;
Identify the lead department/officer in the implementation of the program;
Require the OIC-GSO to provide the Audit Team a copy of PAR once the equipment are issued to the department responsible in the implementation of the said program; and
Ensure the manpower requirement as well as the required skills needed in order to ascertain prompt delivery of service.

We recommended that Management:
Expedite the creation of the M&E Team and define its detailed functions, responsibilities and accountabilities;
Ensure that M&E activities are included in the GPB and that the same are undertaken by the Team;
Require the GFPS-TWG to prepare the GAD AR, complete with required information and accomplishments for PPAs attributed to GAD; and
Post the GAD AR in the LGU’s full disclosure board or in any conspicuous place accessible to public.

We recommended that Management:
Require all Accountable Officers concerned to liquidate their cash advances on time, otherwise, impose administrative sanctions against them for any unjustifiable reasons due to failure to liquidate cash advances within the prescribe period, in accordance with Section 89 of PD 1445, COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 and Civil Service Commission No. 04-0676 dated June 14, 2004;
Strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 in the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;
Cause or order the withholding of any money claims against the accountable officers concerned until they have fully settled their unliquidated cash advances; and
Request for write-off of the unliquidated cash advances of the accountable officers who were already deceased in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended that management dispose the unserviceable properties of the agency in accordance with Sections 76 and 79 of PD 1445.Disposal of these properties may:

generate additional funds, when sold, to be used for the agency’s operations;

relieve the responsible official of accountability over said properties;

prevent said unserviceable properties from further deterioration and loss of value; and allow the agency to use the space being occupied by these unserviceable properties.

We have recommended that management dispose the unserviceable properties of the agency in accordance with Sections 76 and 79 of PD 1445 and that the cost of disposed motor vehicles in the amount of P1,824,840.00 and that of other properties once determined be dropped from the books of accounts of the agency for fair presentation of the PPE and Government Equity accounts in the financial statements.  It is recommended that disposal of these properties is necessary for the following reasons:

generates additional funds, when sold, to be used for the agency’s operations;

relieves the responsible official of accountability over said properties;

prevents said unserviceable properties from further deterioration and loss of value; and

allows the agency to use the space being occupied by these unserviceable properties.

